,"1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Stourton, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire, England","Hooten, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Knowsley, Lancashire, England":"Knowsley, Lancashire, England"},"nl":{"1273–1294":"1273–1294","1273–Female":"1273–Overleden","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1292–1294":"1292–1294","1252–1275":"1252–1275","–Female":"Overleden","Abt 1272":"circa 1272","1345":"1345","about 1290":"circa 1290","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Stourton, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire, England","Hooten, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Knowsley, Lancashire, England":"Knowsley, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1273–1294":"1273–1294","1273–Female":"1273–Deceased","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1292–1294":"1292–1294","1252–1275":"1252–1275","–Female":"Deceased","Abt 1272":"about 1272","1345":"1345","about 1290":"about 1290","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Stourton, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire, England","Hooten, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Knowsley, Lancashire, England":"Knowsley, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hawkset","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: nickname from Middle English  <i>haukeseye</i> ‘hawk’s eye’.","2  English: the Manchester surname Hawksey preserves an old form of   Hawkshaw  , recorded as  <i>Hawkesey</i> in 1527 (   Lancs Place-Names  , p. 63)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hawkshaw","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from Hawkshaw in Tottington (Lancashire), named from Old English <i>hafoc</i> ‘hawk’ + <i>sceaga</i> ‘small wood, copse’."]},{"name":"Lancs Place-Names","meanings":["1  Norman, English: (i) locative name from any of the five places in Normandy named Beaumont (Old French ‘beautiful hill or mound’). The   Domesday Book   family came from Beaumont-le-Roger (Eure). (ii) locative name; the Suffolk name may alternatively derive from Beaumont cum Moze (Essex), a Norman re-naming of a place formerly known as  <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul hollow’, in imitation of one of the places mentioned in (i). It is recorded as  <i>Bealmont</i> (1175–80) and  <i>Beumund</i> (1328) in   Place-Names of Essex  .","2  Norman, English: locative name the Lancs and WR Yorks name is from Beaumont (Lancs), named in imitation of one of the Norman places mentioned in (1). It is recorded as  <i>Belli Montis</i> (1190),  <i>Belmunt</i> (1212),  <i>(de) Beaumont</i> in the 13th century, and  <i>Beamond</i> (about 1320) in   Lancs Place-Names  ."]},{"name":"Hawkey","meanings":["English (Cornwall): variant, with loss of the medial genitive <i>s</i>, of <b>Hawksey</b>, which is a nickname from Middle English <i>haukeseye</i> ‘hawk's eye’ and also a variant of   Hawkshaw  , recorded as <i>Hawkesey</i> in 1527."]}]},{"name":"James","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name borne in the New Testament by two of Christ's disciples, James son of Zebedee and James son of Alphaeus. This form comes from Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of <i>Iacobus</i>, Latin form of Greek <i>Iakobos</i>. This is the same name as Old Testament   Jacob   (Hebrew <i>Yaakov</i>), but for many centuries now they have been thought of in the English-speaking world as two distinct names. In Britain, <i>James</i> is a royal name that from the beginning of the 15th century onwards was associated particularly with the Scottish house of Stewart:  James I  of Scotland (  1394–1437 ; ruled  1424–37 ) was a patron of the arts and a noted poet, as well as an energetic ruler.  King James VI  of Scotland (  1566–1625 ; reigned  1567–1625 ) succeeded to the throne of England in  1603 . His grandson,  James II  of England (  1633–1701 ; reigned  1685–8 ) was a Roman Catholic, deposed in  1688  in favour of his Protestant daughter Mary and her husband William of Orange. From then on he, his son (also called James), and his grandson Charles (‘Bonnie Prince Charlie’) made various unsuccessful attempts to recover the English throne. Their supporters were known as Jacobites (from Latin <i>Iacobus</i>), and the name James became for a while particularly associated with Roman Catholicism on the one hand, and Highland opposition to the English government on the other. Nevertheless, it has since become one of the most perennially popular boys' names."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":17,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"James Hawkset II was born in 1273, in Storeton, Cheshire, England as the son of Sir James Hawkset and Mrs. James Kawksket. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs James Hawkset. He died in 1294, in Knowsley, Lancashire, England, at the age of 21."},"et":{"1273–1294":"1273–1294","1273–Female":"1273–Surnud","1290–1345":"1290–1345","1292–1294":"1292–1294","1252–1275":"1252–1275","–Female":"Surnud","Abt 1272":"umbes 1272","1345":"1345","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1275":"1275","1252":"1252","1273":"1273","1294":"1294","1292":"1292","1290":"1290","Stourton, Wiltshire, England":"Stourton, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Storeton, Cheshire, England":"Storeton, Cheshire